('chunk_0505ad6d35c64fd79c','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Common Misconceptions Master List','1. **Biome = ecosystem.** No — biome is global-scale; ecosystem is local.
2. **Rainforest soil is rich.** No — it is nutrient-poor; richness is in the living plants.
3. **Poles are the rainiest places because they are cold.** No — cold, sinking air is dry; poles are "cold deserts."
4. **Evergreen trees never lose leaves.** No — they shed needles gradually all year.
5. **Deserts are lifeless seas of sand.** No — mostly rocky and full of adapted life; defined by low rainfall.
6. **Savanna fires are always disasters.** No — periodic fire is natural and needed.
7. **Grasslands are empty, unused land.** No — the world''s richest farmland.
8. **Nothing lives in the tundra.** No — caribou, foxes, birds and hardy plants thrive.
9. **Renewable resources can never run out.** No — forests, fish and groundwater can be depleted.
10. **Soil is just dead dirt.** No — living and effectively non-renewable on human timescales.
11. **Only poor/overpopulated countries cause depletion.** No — high per-capita consumption matters as much.
12. **Recycling alone makes an economy circular.** No — reduce and reuse come first.
13. **Sustainable development means stopping growth.** No — it means growing cleaner and fairer.
14. **A rich country is automatically developed.** No — wealth can be unequally shared.
15. **Resource-rich countries are always developed.** No — the "resource curse."
16. **All Global South countries are equally poor.** No — development is a spectrum.
17. **Poverty is caused by laziness.** No — it is largely structural.
18. **There isn''t enough food for everyone.** No — it''s a distribution and waste problem.
19. **Water scarcity only happens in deserts.** No — economic scarcity affects water-rich regions.
20. **Renewable transition is quick and easy.** No — costly, gradual and challenging.
21. **Aid always helps.** No — poorly planned aid can create dependency.','{"common":1,"misconceptions":1,"master":1,"list":1,"biome":2,"ecosystem":2,"global":2,"scale":1,"local":1,"rainforest":1,"soil":2,"rich":4,"nutrient":1,"poor":3,"richness":1,"the":5,"living":2,"plants":2,"poles":2,"are":8,"rainiest":1,"places":1,"because":1,"they":2,"cold":3,"sinking":1,"air":1,"dry":1,"deserts":3,"evergreen":1,"trees":1,"never":2,"lose":1,"leaves":1,"shed":1,"needles":1,"gradually":1,"all":2,"year":1,"lifeless":1,"seas":1,"sand":1,"mostly":1,"rocky":1,"and":10,"full":1,"adapted":1,"life":1,"defined":1,"low":1,"rainfall":1,"savanna":1,"fires":1,"always":3,"disasters":1,"periodic":1,"fire":1,"natural":1,"needed":1,"grasslands":1,"empty":1,"unused":1,"land":1,"world":1,"richest":1,"farmland":1,"nothing":1,"lives":1,"tundra":1,"caribou":1,"foxes":1,"birds":1,"hardy":1,"thrive":1,"renewable":3,"resources":1,"can":4,"run":1,"out":1,"forests":1,"fish":1,"groundwater":1,"depleted":1,"just":1,"dead":1,"dirt":1,"effectively":1,"non":1,"human":1,"timescales":1,"only":2,"overpopulated":1,"countries":3,"cause":1,"depletion":1,"high":1,"per":1,"capita":1,"consumption":1,"matters":1,"much":1,"recycling":1,"alone":1,"makes":1,"economy":1,"circular":1,"reduce":1,"reuse":1,"come":1,"first":1,"sustainable":1,"development":2,"means":2,"stopping":1,"growth":1,"growing":1,"cleaner":1,"fairer":1,"country":1,"automatically":1,"developed":2,"wealth":1,"unequally":1,"shared":1,"resource":2,"curse":1,"south":1,"equally":1,"spectrum":1,"poverty":1,"caused":1,"laziness":1,"largely":1,"structural":1,"there":1,"isn":1,"enough":1,"food":1,"for":1,"everyone":1,"distribution":1,"waste":1,"problem":1,"water":2,"scarcity":2,"happens":1,"economic":1,"affects":1,"regions":1,"transition":1,"quick":1,"easy":1,"costly":1,"gradual":1,"challenging":1,"aid":2,"helps":1,"poorly":1,"planned":1,"create":1,"dependency":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_dc29525115151e9329','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Command-Term / GRASPS Question Bank','1. **Define** "biome" and **outline** two factors that determine biome distribution. *(Criterion A)*
2. **Compare and contrast** the tropical rainforest and the taiga in terms of climate, soil and human use. Present your answer as a table. *(Criterion A/C)*
3. **GRASPS task:** *Goal* — advise a government; *Role* — you are a sustainability consultant; *Audience* — the Ministry of Environment; *Situation* — rapid deforestation; *Product* — a one-page conservation strategy proposal; *Standards* — uses named examples, the 3 Rs and SDG links. *(Criterion C/D)*
4. **Investigate** (Criterion B): "How does water scarcity affect daily life in a named water-stressed region?" Write a research question, plan and list two sources.
5. **OPVL / source analysis:** You are given a photograph of Amazon deforestation and a mining company''s press release. **Evaluate** the **Origin, Purpose, Value and Limitation** of each source, and explain how each shapes the message. *(Criterion D)*
6. **OPVL / source analysis:** Examine a choropleth map of HDI. **Analyse** what it shows about the North–South divide and **identify two limitations** of using such a map. *(Criterion D)*
7. **To what extent** is international aid an effective way to promote long-term development? Use at least one case study. *(Criterion D)*
